import numpy as np
from astropy.io import fits
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.colors import LogNorm
#3a, b
hdulist = fits.open('sdss_sample.fits')
data = hdulist[1].data 
modelmag_g = data['modelmag_g']
modelmag_r = data['modelmag_r']
dist = data['dist']
color = modelmag_g - modelmag_r
dist_pc = dist * 1e6
M_r = modelmag_r - 5 * (np.log10(dist_pc) - 1)

# Filter out extreme values (e.g., for visualization clarity)
mask = (color > 0.2) & (color < 1.5) & (M_r > -25) & (M_r < -11)
M_r_filtered = M_r[mask]
color_filtered = color[mask]
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
plt.hist2d(M_r_filtered, color_filtered, bins=[200, 200], cmap='plasma')
plt.xlabel(r'$M_r$')
plt.ylabel(r'$(g - r)$')
plt.colorbar(label='Number of Galaxies')
plt.title('Color-Magnitude Diagram')
x = np.linspace(M_r_filtered.min(), M_r_filtered.max(), 100)
y = -0.065* x -0.63
plt.plot(x, y, color='black', linestyle='--', linewidth=2, label='Dividing Line')
plt.text(-22, 0.55, 'Blue Cloud', color='white', fontsize=12)
plt.text(-23, 1, 'Red Sequence', color='white', fontsize=12)
plt.legend()
plt.show()

#3c
lgm_tot_p50 = data['lgm_tot_p50']
sfr_tot_p50 = data['sfr_tot_p50']
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.scatter(lgm_tot_p50, sfr_tot_p50, s=1, alpha=0.5)  # Scatter plot with transparency for clarity
plt.xlabel(r'$\log(M_*)$ [M$_\odot$]')
plt.ylabel(r'$\log(\mathrm{SFR})$ [M$_\odot$ yr$^{-1}$]')
plt.title('Log SFR vs. Log Stellar Mass')
plt.grid(True)
plt.yscale('log')
plt.ylim(1e-6, 1e1)
plt.show()

For a regular 10^10 solar masses galaxy, the average SFR would be 0.25 solar mass per year. The lowest quiescent galaxy typically has a mass of 2*10^10 solar masses.

#3f
spiral_flag = data['t04_spiral_a08_spiral_flag']
bulge_flag = data['t05_bulge_prominence_a12_obvious_flag']
spiral_mask = spiral_flag == 1
bulge_mask = bulge_flag == 1
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 6))

# Spiral Galaxies
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.scatter(lgm_tot_p50[spiral_mask], sfr_tot_p50[spiral_mask], s=1, alpha=0.5, color='green')
plt.xlabel(r'$\log(M_*)$ [M$_\odot$]')
plt.ylabel(r'$\log(\mathrm{SFR})$ [M$_\odot$ yr$^{-1}$]')
plt.title('Log SFR vs. Log Stellar Mass (Spiral Galaxies)')
plt.grid(True)
plt.yscale('log')
plt.ylim(1e-5, 1e1)
# Bulge-Dominated Galaxies
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.scatter(lgm_tot_p50[bulge_mask], sfr_tot_p50[bulge_mask], s=1, alpha=0.5, color='brown')
plt.xlabel(r'$\log(M_*)$ [M$_\odot$]')
plt.ylabel(r'$\log(\mathrm{SFR})$ [M$_\odot$ yr$^{-1}$]')
plt.title('Log SFR vs. Log Stellar Mass (Bulge-Dominated Galaxies)')
plt.grid(True)
plt.yscale('log')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.ylim(1e-5, 1e1)
plt.show()

Spiral Galaxies: Typically, spiral galaxies are actively star-forming and will have higher SFR values compared to bulge-dominated galaxies of similar mass.

Bulge-Dominated Galaxies: These galaxies are often quiescent with low SFR, corresponding to the red sequence.
